#typhus #scrubTyphus #infection

[!INFO]
Epidemic typhus serves as the prototype disease in the group and has more severe clinical manifestations.
Murine and scrub typhus are milder.

Presentation

[!TIP] Typhus => Fever, lymphadenopathy, lymphopenia, thrombocytopenia, ESCHAR,
Typhus involves the lyphoid system -> atypical lymphocytes, lymphadenopathy, lymphopenia etc
Suspect with Fever + tender lymphadenopathy + travel history -> then FBC will show lymphopenia, hypoalbuminaemia, atypical lymphocytes

Incubation period is 12 days.

  • Fever (prolonged; about 2 weeks if untreated), headache, fatigue
  • body pain
  • Mental changes
  • Lymphadenopathy - regional or generalized tender lymphadenopathy
  • Rash - a small, painless, gradually enlarging papule, which leads to an area of central necrosis and is followed by eschar formation
  • eschar (occurs in 50% of patients, not all)
  • Pneumonitis or encephalitis, Central nervous system (CNS), pulmonary, or cardiac involvement, Rarely, acute renal failure, shock, and disseminated intravascular coagulation (DIC) - potentially fatal disease
  • may have splenomegaly
  • In #pregnancy , scrub typhus frequently leads to spontaneous abortions.Source

Travel History to endemic region (incubation period = 10 days)

Pathogenesis

Epidemic typhus Scrub Typhus
Body louse: Pediculis Corporis Tombiculid mite
Pathogen: Ricketsia prowazekii Orientia tsutsugamushi
Can be severe (with high mortality) Usually milder

#insect-vector
Endemic typhus serves as the prototype for pathogenesis:

The body louse carries ricketsia in it's gut. Tick bite causes itching and during itching tick faeces are inoculated into the the bite site.
Ricketsia enter the blood stream and infect the endothelium causing systemic vasculitis.
May cause decreased perfusion to organs and necrosis of extremities (Nose,ear lobes, genitalia.
Vasculitis -> loss of intravascular colloid -> ?cause of hypoalbuminaemia
Electrolyte loss is common.

Brill-Zinsser disease: recrudescence of typhus months to many years after apparently successful treatment.

Murine and scrub typhus are generally milder than epidemic typhus.

Epidemic typhus causes the most severe clinical presentation -> severe epidemic typhus may develop gangrene, leading to a loss of digits, limbs, or other appendage.
High mortality -> lowest estimate is 20%

Scrub typhus

Transmitted via larval tick bite. (trombiculid mites)
Pathogen: Bacterium - Orientia tsutsugamushi : Obligate intracellular pathogen, belongs to ricketsia.

Diagnosis

Haematology

  • Early lymphopenia with late lymphocytosis + atypical lymphocytes in blood pic.
  • Decreased CD4:CD8 lymphocyte ratio
  • Thrombocytopenia
  • Hematologic manifestations may be confused with dengue infection

Biochemical

  • Elevated transaminase levels (75-95% of patients)
  • Hypoalbuminemia (50% of cases)

Direct evidence

  • Weil - Felix test - not sensitive or specific; is a heterophile antibody test based on shared antigens between ricketsia and proteus. Should be carried out 5 - 7 days after onset of fever. slideshare presentation
  • An infection is confirmed by a 4-fold increase in antibody titers between acute and convalescent serum specimens - (serologic testing not useful acutely). IgM appears in 1 week, IgG appears in 2 weeks.
  • Immunofluorescense assay (IFA) - Gold standard but expensive. #immunofluorescence #goldStandard

Known antigen is immobilized on a glass slide. Test serum is added over the smear. If specific antibodies are present in the serum, the antigen-antibody complex is formed. The serum is washed off and a secondary antihuman immunoglobulin conjugated to a fluorochrome is added. Upon examination under fluorescence microscope, bacteria will only be visible if they have been bound by the antibodies from the patient’s serum.

Treatment

#doxycycline
Doxycycline - inhibits protein synthesis by binding to the 30s ribosomal subunit.

Epidemic typhus

Caused by - Ricketsia prowazekii.
This is actually the prototypical illness of the typhus group.
Transmitted by the body louse: Pediculus corporis. The only typhus vectors who's usual host is human!

Behçet syndrome / Behcet disease

#2021GM-NOV Q26

[!INFO] Behcet's disease main features: PATHERGY TEST


Chronic systemic inflammation
Unknown etiology.
unique for involvement of vessels of all sizes!

[!INFO] The single most important clinical finding
Most important clinical manifestation is recurrent mucocutaneous ulcers.

  • painful, oral and genital ulcers are almost universal. Most common presenting complaints.
  • Scrotum / major and minor labia.
  • They occur in the first few years. Can cause scarring.
  • Erythema nodosum and erythema multiforme , superficial thrombophlebitis can occur.
  • Occular disease:
    • Posterior (most common) or pan uveitisi, retinal vasculitis
  • Assymetric oligoarthritis, medium to large lesions.
  • unsually, veins are more commonly affected than arteries:
    • Budd chiari syndrome
    • Cerebral venous thrombosis
    • venous thrombosis
    • SVC and IVC
    • pulmonary artery aneurysm are somewhat specific for behcets but are rare.
  • Neurologic compliations:
    • Encephalitis, cranial nerve palsies, ataxia and myelopathy.
  • GI pathology:
    • Ulcers in the ileoceoal region similar appearance to Crohn's disease.
  • Malaise, fatigue and periodic fevers.

Presents between 20 and 40 years old.
"Silk road disease" - europe, persia, india china. Turkey has x 100 the incidence.

It is a clinical diagnosis. There is no confirmatory tests.
Pathergy test: Development of a papule or pustule-like lesion 48 hours after skin prick by 20 guage needle.

Behcet's disease: diagnostic criteria

Behcets disease: treatment

Attack rate

the "proportion of those who become ill after a specified exposure over a specified time period"
Or
The "proportion of exposed people who become ill".

1. *Live attenuated* influenza - (also contraindicated in close contacts / caregivers of immunosuppressed patients!)
1. *Live attenuated* influenza vaccine (NOT the killed IV vaccine)

Varicella zoster vaccination

Varicella zoster is a highly infectious virus transmitted through inhalation of aerosolized droplets. Initially presents as upper airway infection which enters the circulation in 2 - 3 days. Second bout of viraemia occurs in 10-12 days when it presents with the rash.
Rash begins on face and trunk and spreads outwards to extremities.
Resolves in 4 - 7 days.

Varicella zoster immunoglobulin

It reduces the severity and attack rate of primary varicella.

Indications

Should be given

  • immediately (upto 10 days) after exposure to immunocompromised patients.
  • Pregnant women lacking evidence of immunity.
  • Newborns who's mothers develop signs of varicella between 5 days before and 2 days after delivery. Mnemonic: "5b4 and 2da"
  • premature newborns whose mother don't have immunity to varicella.

Influenza vaccine

The vaccine is made by

  • Cell culture methods
  • Egg based flu vaccine (can produce live attenuated and killed vaccines)
  • Recombinant vaccines.

The live attenuated influenza vaccines are given via nasal spray. They care contraindicated in pregnancy and ?immunosuppressed people.
The killed vaccine the one given IV.
